      "question": "The graph of a polynomial $p(x) = ax^2 + bx + c$, where $a \\neq 0$, touches the $x$-axis at exactly one point $P(2, 0)$. If the graph also passes through the point $Q(0, 4)$, which of the following statements is true regarding its zeroes?",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Since the graph touches the $x$-axis at $(2, 0)$, the polynomial has two coincident zeroes at $x = 2$.",
          "A quadratic polynomial with coincident zeroes at $x = k$ can be written in the form $p(x) = a(x - k)^2$.",
          "Substituting $k = 2$, we get $p(x) = a(x - 2)^2$.",
          "Given that the graph passes through $(0, 4)$, substitute $x = 0$ and $p(x) = 4$ to find $a$: $4 = a(0 - 2)^2 \\Rightarrow 4 = 4a \\Rightarrow a = 1$.",
          "The polynomial is $p(x) = (x - 2)^2$.",
          "The zeroes are $x = 2, 2$, which are both positive and equal."
        ],
        "derivation": "$p(x) = a(x - 2)^2 \\\\ 4 = a(0 - 2)^2 \\\\ 4 = 4a \\\\ a = 1 \\\\ p(x) = (x - 2)^2 \\\\ \\text{Zeroes are } 2, 2 \\\\ \\text{Both zeroes are positive}$"
      },
      "topic": "Polynomials",
      "subtopic": "geometrical meaning of zeros",
